WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:02.877
[Charles-Haden Savage]
<i>Marshall, we need to talk with you.</i>

00:02.878 --> 00:04.837
I thought you wanted to give me
more notes on the script.

00:04.838 --> 00:07.215
<i>Everyone's been hounding me
about rewrites.</i>

00:07.216 --> 00:09.258
Every draft that Marshall turns in
is worse than the last.

00:09.259 --> 00:12.094
Loretta and I shall
marry here in the Arconia.

00:12.095 --> 00:13.513
[Charles, Mabel, Oliver]
Sazz!

00:13.514 --> 00:15.681
There's something I need to talk to you
about when you get a sec, huh?

00:15.682 --> 00:17.266
- It's a little sensitive.
- So, you don't know

00:17.267 --> 00:18.601
<i>- who the target was?</i>
- [gunshot]

00:18.602 --> 00:20.728
<i>The person who did this
would have to be extremely fit</i>.

00:20.729 --> 00:23.397
A gifted athlete in
the best shape of their life.

00:23.398 --> 00:25.483
Sazz talked about a stuntman

00:25.484 --> 00:28.236
on a movie called <i>Project Ronkonkoma.</i>

00:28.237 --> 00:30.780
<i>He was her protégé,
but he had messed up pretty badly,</i>

00:30.781 --> 00:32.072
<i>and he was harassing her.</i>

00:32.073 --> 00:34.450
The only ones who know what went down

00:34.451 --> 00:36.452
<i>- are Sazz, Glen, and the director.</i>
- [muffled yelling]

00:36.453 --> 00:38.120
He's dead, my Glen.

00:38.121 --> 00:40.831
[newscaster] [on TV] <i>Nicky Caccimelio
has been reported missing.</i>

00:40.832 --> 00:43.543
We heard there was quite the snafu
on <i>Project Ronkonkoma.</i>

00:43.544 --> 00:44.627
[screams]

00:44.628 --> 00:46.963
[bartender] The guy fucked up so bad,
Sazz had to blackball him.

00:46.964 --> 00:49.590
- Who was this protégé?
- Here he is.

00:49.591 --> 00:50.800
[Charles]
That kinda looks like...

00:50.801 --> 00:54.221
Why does this script say
it was written by Sazz Pataki?

00:54.596 --> 00:56.014
[text notification chimes]

01:01.603 --> 01:03.187
[♪ dramatic electronic music playing]

01:03.188 --> 01:08.067
[Sazz Pataki] <i>A movie is a hundred people
working together to tell one story.</i>

01:08.068 --> 01:10.778
[yelling groan] That's right, Kincaid!

01:10.779 --> 01:12.029
It's me, Uncle Brazzos,

01:12.030 --> 01:15.658
and I can still send this investigation
into a whole new direction!

01:15.659 --> 01:17.159
[director]
Freeze! Tap in.

01:17.160 --> 01:18.327
[Sazz]
Tap in!

01:18.328 --> 01:21.123
♪

01:21.790 --> 01:23.208
And action!

01:25.377 --> 01:26.460
[airbag hisses]

01:26.461 --> 01:28.004
- [Sazz] I'm good!
- [director] Cut!

01:28.005 --> 01:29.589
- [alarm ringing]
- Check the gate!

01:29.590 --> 01:31.424
- Woo!
- [set chatter]

01:31.425 --> 01:32.758
Nice job, Pataki!

01:32.759 --> 01:34.594
[Sazz panting]

01:34.595 --> 01:36.053
- [♪ soft music playing]
- Woo!

01:36.054 --> 01:38.014
<i>Every person on the crew,</i>

01:38.015 --> 01:41.309
<i>their job is to help tell the story.</i>

01:41.310 --> 01:42.935
<i>Some tell it with music.</i>

01:42.936 --> 01:45.521
<i>Some tell it with props. Me?</i>

01:45.522 --> 01:48.442
<i>I tell it with osteoporosis.</i>

01:49.651 --> 01:51.778
[panting]

01:52.905 --> 01:56.825
<i>Sometimes, it doesn't sound terrible
to tell a story the old-fashioned way</i>.

01:58.702 --> 02:01.330
<i>Without breaking
all my bones in the process</i>.

02:02.748 --> 02:03.999
<i>But where to begin?</i>

02:06.043 --> 02:09.504
<i>Well, I suppose it starts
with finding your hero.</i>

02:09.505 --> 02:10.631
[Charles]
Hey, Sazz, you okay?

02:11.798 --> 02:13.591
- All good, buddy.
- [Charles] Thank you.

02:13.592 --> 02:15.510
- I'm getting worse with heights. Uh--
- [staff chattering]

02:15.511 --> 02:18.179
Ah, I got you.
Don't you worry about a thing.

02:18.180 --> 02:21.307
[chatter continues]

02:21.308 --> 02:24.977
♪

02:24.978 --> 02:26.062
[typewriter typing]

02:26.063 --> 02:28.648
[Charles] [on podcast]
<i>As it turned out, we are all Tim Kono.</i>

02:28.649 --> 02:30.483
[Sazz]
<i>When you take your hero on a journey,</i>

02:30.484 --> 02:32.235
<i>get him in all kinds of trouble,</i>

02:32.236 --> 02:34.571
<i>but land him home safely</i>?

02:36.240 --> 02:38.242
<i>Nothing better than that</i>.

02:40.035 --> 02:41.494
[flaps paper]

02:41.495 --> 02:45.540
<i>But happy endings are for movies
and exotic massages.</i>

02:45.541 --> 02:49.002
<i>Life can have very different plans.</i>

02:50.045 --> 02:53.714
So, the killer is Rex Bailey
slash Marshall P. Pope

02:53.715 --> 02:56.968
slash the stuntman
slash the screenwriter slash

02:56.969 --> 02:58.886
what the fuck is going on?

02:58.887 --> 03:01.430
Where is the young one?
We need a pliable brain on this.

03:01.431 --> 03:03.432
I texted Mabel
the minute we figured it out,

03:03.433 --> 03:05.894
but she hasn't responded. Look.

03:07.229 --> 03:10.606
How did you get that little accent mark
on the E in protégé?

03:10.607 --> 03:13.192
Oh, you press and hold down
the letter you want the accent over,

03:13.193 --> 03:15.486
then you get a list of accent choices.

03:15.487 --> 03:17.197
- No kidding! [laughs]
- It's fun, right?

03:17.364 --> 03:18.531
Yeah, Mabel taught me that.

03:18.532 --> 03:20.117
- [shuts off phone]
- You know,

03:21.243 --> 03:24.287
every time we solve a murder,
that's when the next body drops.

03:24.288 --> 03:26.122
It's like when one murder door closes,

03:26.123 --> 03:29.918
someone we know either gets
stabbed, poisoned, or shot.

03:31.044 --> 03:33.296
Why would you say that?

03:33.297 --> 03:34.881
You know my wedding is tomorrow.

03:34.882 --> 03:37.466
Loretta's on her way now,
here to the murder building.

03:37.467 --> 03:39.260
I wasn't saying it'd be Loretta.

03:39.261 --> 03:41.762
Well, you were basically
saying that, Charles.

03:41.763 --> 03:43.014
[sighs deeply]

03:43.015 --> 03:44.640
Oh, my God.

03:44.641 --> 03:46.934
My bride is gonna be
the next murder victim.

03:46.935 --> 03:48.769
It's so us. And to think, up until now,

03:48.770 --> 03:52.231
my only worry was
what our first dance should be.

03:52.232 --> 03:54.150
And whether watching
Loretta and I do a tango

03:54.151 --> 03:56.861
might be too erotic
for everyone to handle.

03:56.862 --> 03:58.696
- [sighs]
- [text notification chimes]

03:58.697 --> 04:00.531
It's from Mabel.

04:00.532 --> 04:03.618
"Call the police or come
anywhere near her door

04:03.619 --> 04:05.578
and I'll kill her"?

04:05.579 --> 04:08.290
[♪ dramatic music playing]

04:18.842 --> 04:22.345
- [gasping]
- [♪ lively theme song playing]

04:22.346 --> 04:25.432
[♪ vocalizing]

05:05.430 --> 05:07.432
[♪ theme song fades out]

05:08.853 --> 05:11.478
[♪ tense music playing]

05:12.813 --> 05:15.898
Can you excuse me for a second?
I'm just gonna go grab--

05:15.899 --> 05:16.983
[Marshall grunts]

05:16.984 --> 05:18.318
You're not going anywhere.

05:20.654 --> 05:22.656
You're pretty fit for a writer.

05:24.908 --> 05:27.077
Because you were a stuntman.

05:28.495 --> 05:30.747
Sazz's protégé.

05:34.168 --> 05:36.210
You stole her script,
and then you killed her.

05:36.211 --> 05:38.212
I can't believe I have to kill you, too.

05:38.213 --> 05:40.298
It was just supposed to be Sazz,
but now look at me.

05:40.299 --> 05:42.800
Sniping, smothering, it never ends.

05:42.801 --> 05:44.845
So, you admit you killed Glen.

05:45.512 --> 05:47.138
I didn't want to.

05:47.139 --> 05:49.223
I never want to,
but it was only a matter of time

05:49.224 --> 05:51.184
before he realized why I looked familiar.

05:51.185 --> 05:53.979
I hate that I accidentally shot
Zach Galifianakis.

05:54.897 --> 05:56.189
He's so funny in <i>The Hangover.</i>

05:56.190 --> 05:59.109
Don't fuckin' move, Mabel!

05:59.860 --> 06:01.111
Okay.

06:02.237 --> 06:04.530
[laughs] Okay.

06:04.531 --> 06:06.116
Well, then,

06:06.491 --> 06:08.493
you can kill me, but...

06:09.077 --> 06:12.414
you're on your own with the whole rewrite.

06:14.124 --> 06:15.958
Oh, I know what you're doing.

06:15.959 --> 06:18.711
Y-You're trying to buy time.
I-I'm not falling for that.

06:18.712 --> 06:21.297
No, you're in charge of this...

06:21.298 --> 06:23.382
whole thing. I just-- Can I?

06:23.383 --> 06:25.718
[♪ soft music playing]

06:25.719 --> 06:28.554
You have, um, Charles...

06:28.555 --> 06:30.598
logging onto AOL.

06:30.599 --> 06:31.724
Yeah, 'cause he's old.

06:31.725 --> 06:33.851
No, I've taught him better than that.

06:33.852 --> 06:36.939
And then, you have Mabel...
[scoffs] saying,

06:37.814 --> 06:39.608
"You've got fail."

06:40.859 --> 06:42.861
Are you sure you wanna go with that?

06:45.906 --> 06:47.407
Fuck.

06:48.825 --> 06:50.618
Fine.

06:50.619 --> 06:53.080
W-We finish the scene,
and then I'll kill you.

06:54.915 --> 06:56.457
Shouldn't we be running to Mabel?

06:56.458 --> 06:57.542
[cars honking down below]

06:57.543 --> 07:00.962
Not that I don't love watching you
stare out a window like a sad war widow.

07:00.963 --> 07:02.505
Oh, my God.

07:02.506 --> 07:04.216
It was one person.

07:05.008 --> 07:07.301
The ledge, that ledge.

07:07.302 --> 07:09.095
It's been right there
in plain sight all along.

07:09.096 --> 07:11.138
[Oliver Putnam]
Who the hell would walk out on that?

07:11.139 --> 07:13.182
A murderous stuntman would.

07:13.183 --> 07:15.059
That's how the shoe print
got on the radiator!

07:15.060 --> 07:17.144
That's how he did it in 12 minutes!

07:17.145 --> 07:18.896
And it's the only way we can save Mabel.

07:18.897 --> 07:20.857
- Abso-- Wait, what?
- Marshall said,

07:20.858 --> 07:23.109
if we go to the door,
he's gonna kill Mabel.

07:23.110 --> 07:26.821
So, we walk along the ledge
and smuggle her out.

07:26.822 --> 07:29.448
This is actually really smart.

07:29.449 --> 07:31.242
He'll never see us coming
through the window.

07:31.243 --> 07:32.410
Okay.

07:32.411 --> 07:34.370
You can drop the word "us"

07:34.371 --> 07:37.456
'cause ol' Ollie Putnam
don't walk no ledge.

07:37.457 --> 07:39.125
I need to do this.

07:39.126 --> 07:40.793
I didn't save Sazz,

07:40.794 --> 07:42.795
but I can save Mabel.

07:42.796 --> 07:45.631
- [♪ curious, tense music playing]
- [window creaks]

07:45.632 --> 07:46.716
[Charles groans]

07:46.717 --> 07:48.509
- [wind blowing]
- [street noise below]

07:48.510 --> 07:51.096
Okay! It's really high up!

07:53.473 --> 07:56.393
Wh-What if you do it from Vince's?
I-It's right next door.

07:58.979 --> 08:01.939
That is the first good pitch you've had
since this whole thing started.

08:01.940 --> 08:04.108
It took four seasons,

08:04.109 --> 08:06.235
but now I'm cookin' with gas!

08:06.236 --> 08:07.321
[elevator dings]

08:09.031 --> 08:11.449
Oliver! Your <i>chuppah</i> arrived.
Where are we placing it?

08:11.450 --> 08:13.826
Lester, I have urgent business,
so I need you to take over.

08:13.827 --> 08:16.287
Now, I trust you completely, but just know

08:16.288 --> 08:18.497
if you get anything wrong,
I will destroy you.

08:18.498 --> 08:20.917
- [Charles grunts]
- What? All he does is let in murderers.

08:20.918 --> 08:23.711
Oh! My bride's in the courtyard. Okay.

08:23.712 --> 08:26.631
Charles! I got married in
this courtyard, you know?

08:26.632 --> 08:28.841
- Middle of the night with just the stars.
- Yeah. Uh-huh.

08:28.842 --> 08:30.009
And the fountain as our witness.

08:30.010 --> 08:31.469
- [Charles] Uh-huh.
- I think it's good luck.

08:31.470 --> 08:34.013
Lester, I told you when I moved in,
I don't really do anecdotes,

08:34.014 --> 08:35.265
but have a good day.

08:37.267 --> 08:39.477
Eh, having a wedding.
We'll have a good day, sure.

08:39.478 --> 08:42.230
- [wheels rattling]
- [Loretta sighs]

08:42.231 --> 08:43.357
[door opens]

08:44.149 --> 08:45.733
Oh! That's nice. Okay.

08:45.734 --> 08:49.111
- You're here!
- Oh! Oliver, oh, my God, my show!

08:49.112 --> 08:51.405
I don't think I can marry you now.

08:51.406 --> 08:54.033
- What?
- Production's moving to New Zealand

08:54.034 --> 08:56.577
because algorithm feels it's newer.

08:56.578 --> 08:59.664
Yeah, so NORFBUN is gonna be NZFBUN,

08:59.665 --> 09:01.749
and I have to move to New Zealand
day after tomorrow!

09:01.750 --> 09:03.417
Oh God, catch up when you can!

09:03.418 --> 09:05.753
Okay, so, uh, m-maybe you can just quit.

09:05.754 --> 09:08.005
- Oh, I can't quit.
- Then, I will move!

09:08.006 --> 09:10.758
Married people move for each other!
Th-That's what we'll do, okay?

09:10.759 --> 09:12.552
- Where are you going?
- I-I will explain later.

09:12.553 --> 09:14.846
Just go to my apartment, lock the door,

09:14.847 --> 09:17.723
and don't answer it for anyone!
And I love you.

09:17.724 --> 09:18.809
[Oliver sighs]

09:20.769 --> 09:22.770
[Rudy Thurber]
Okay, left one in front, not the right.

09:22.771 --> 09:24.856
- [Vince Fish] Oh. That's more difficult.
- There you go. Yeah.

09:24.857 --> 09:28.318
[loud banging at door]

09:29.820 --> 09:32.613
Oh, great timing! I'm just doing this
new thing called exercise.

09:32.614 --> 09:34.323
- You wanna join?
- He hired me to be his trainer.

09:34.324 --> 09:36.075
- [Oliver] Uh-huh.
- We need to use your window!

09:36.076 --> 09:37.618
Mabel's trapped next door with the killer.

09:37.619 --> 09:39.579
- [Vince] Oh God!
- It's the movie writer, incidentally.

09:39.580 --> 09:41.414
I told you it wasn't us.

09:41.415 --> 09:44.292
We're just a bunch of cute weirdos
who torched a body.

09:44.293 --> 09:45.543
You want us to call the police?

09:45.544 --> 09:47.461
- [Oliver] No, no, no.
- No! He'll kill her if we do.

09:47.462 --> 09:49.881
I will not be joining
because I'm not insane,

09:49.882 --> 09:52.550
but I will be contributing
to today's caper

09:52.551 --> 09:54.302
by creating a front door distraction.

09:54.303 --> 09:57.346
Front door distraction.
Now, is that a type of ding-dong?

09:57.347 --> 09:59.390
It is, Rudy! Very good.

09:59.391 --> 10:01.726
- Ding-dong.
- [Oliver] Charles! Wait, wait, wait.

10:01.727 --> 10:04.562
If you fall, angle your body away
from my wedding. Everything's a rental.

10:04.563 --> 10:07.648
- [♪ dramatic music playing]
- [wind blowing]

10:07.649 --> 10:09.735
[both groan]

10:11.069 --> 10:12.070
[Oliver growls]

10:13.447 --> 10:17.408
- Oh... Okay.
- Okay. [nervous laugh] Alright.

10:17.409 --> 10:20.203
- Yeah. I got it.
- [Oliver whimpers]

10:20.204 --> 10:22.788
[laughs] I got it-- [gasps]

10:22.789 --> 10:24.916
- Watch it! Watch it! Oh...
- [Charles grunting]

10:24.917 --> 10:26.584
[yelling]

10:26.585 --> 10:28.711
- Ah!
- Oh, Sazz.

10:28.712 --> 10:30.046
Sazz, I need you.

10:30.047 --> 10:31.507
♪

10:34.259 --> 10:35.301
[gasps]

10:35.302 --> 10:37.178
Okay, ghost of Sazz.

10:37.179 --> 10:39.180
Anytime you wanna tap in.

10:39.181 --> 10:41.849
- [♪ dramatic music playing]
- Anytime...

10:41.850 --> 10:44.101
[gasps] Oh, I can't do it, Sazz.

10:44.102 --> 10:46.562
Oh, I can't do it by myself.

10:46.563 --> 10:48.147
[♪ music swells]

10:48.148 --> 10:50.107
[panting] That's why I'm here.

10:50.108 --> 10:51.484
Now, be honest.

10:51.485 --> 10:53.862
Are you on this ledge
'cause I'm moving to New Zealand?

10:54.655 --> 10:57.281
I think you know I'm trying to save Mabel,
so g-go back.

10:57.282 --> 10:59.867
No, no, Charles, you're my ride or die.

10:59.868 --> 11:02.370
- [traffic noise below]
- And my strong preference is to ride.

11:02.371 --> 11:03.956
So, scoot! Scoot.

11:04.623 --> 11:06.542
- [Charles grunting]
- [cars honking below]

11:07.042 --> 11:08.417
I can't move my feet.

11:08.418 --> 11:10.962
Yes, because you're looking down
at certain death!

11:10.963 --> 11:13.841
- [♪ tense music playing]
- We gotta do this facing the wall.

11:15.050 --> 11:17.134
Are you suggesting we pivot?

11:17.135 --> 11:19.303
- We are in the sky!
- Charles!

11:19.304 --> 11:23.015
That is Mabel through that window.
Now, you lost Sazz.

11:23.016 --> 11:24.475
We can't lose her, too.

11:24.476 --> 11:26.686
So, here we go, okay?

11:26.687 --> 11:29.313
Now, spin on three. One.

11:29.314 --> 11:31.440
Two. Three.

11:31.441 --> 11:33.818
- Spin!
- [both scream]

11:33.819 --> 11:35.278
[Oliver wails]

11:35.279 --> 11:38.739
Oh! Okay. Okay, yeah.

11:38.740 --> 11:42.202
Excellent! The rest of the way,
we merengue. [snorts]

11:43.161 --> 11:45.288
See, to me, this doesn't read
as a dance moment.

11:45.289 --> 11:47.957
Yes, but I realized
it is my wedding dance.

11:47.958 --> 11:50.210
So, uh, just watch and learn.

11:50.794 --> 11:52.670
- [wind blowing]
- Step, drag.

11:52.671 --> 11:59.260
- Step, drag. Step, drag.
- Step, drag. Step, drag.

11:59.261 --> 12:02.221
[groans] And I thought
I didn't have rhythm. Ah!

12:02.222 --> 12:07.518
Step, drag. Step, drag.

12:07.519 --> 12:10.062
- [stammering] Go. Go. Go.
- [muffled yelling]

12:10.063 --> 12:11.898
- [doorbell rings]
- Come up with some fuckin' idea, like...

12:11.899 --> 12:12.982
[Oliver gasps]

12:12.983 --> 12:14.192
- Wait.
- What?

12:14.193 --> 12:17.236
If you're here, who's doing the ding-dong?

12:17.237 --> 12:19.655
[Rudy] Hello!
It's friendly neighbors Rudy and Vince.

12:19.656 --> 12:21.407
[Vince]
We wanna borrow some sugar!

12:21.408 --> 12:23.284
Uh, you know, like friendly neighbors do.

12:23.285 --> 12:26.954
[in Southern accent] Uh, M-Mabel's not...
Mabel's not here right now!

12:26.955 --> 12:28.831
M-Maybe y'all wanna come back later?

12:28.832 --> 12:31.000
We're making sugar chicken!

12:31.001 --> 12:33.169
A-And it's-- We've never done it before,

12:33.170 --> 12:35.755
and we're trying to figure out
anything that might work!

12:35.756 --> 12:38.674
[Rudy] Do you have any corn on the cob?
O-Or off the cob?

12:38.675 --> 12:41.511
How about-- What are those little pickles?
What are they, they gherkins?

12:41.512 --> 12:42.803
- Or corbishons?
- [window tapping]

12:42.804 --> 12:43.888
[Rudy]
Cornichons.

12:43.889 --> 12:45.598
- [Vince] Cornichons? Cornichons!
- [Marshall P. Pope] Uh...

12:45.599 --> 12:47.475
[in Scottish accent]
Lads, we're kinda busy right now!

12:47.476 --> 12:51.354
[Vince] Uh, well, it's whatever you have
is really what we're looking for!

12:51.355 --> 12:53.314
[sighs] [whispering]
Thank God you're here.

12:53.315 --> 12:55.274
- [Rudy] Yeah, like half a banana...
- [whispering] Charles!

12:55.275 --> 12:57.026
We are not going inside.

12:57.027 --> 12:58.402
Merengue back out here right now!

12:58.403 --> 13:00.530
[Marshall] Frankly, there's no food
in here and I don't understand...

13:00.531 --> 13:02.490
- No. He killed Sazz.
- [Marshall] ...what you're cooking!

13:02.491 --> 13:04.325
Oh, that's alright! We'll just look!

13:04.326 --> 13:06.787
Yeah, w-we'll just come on in,
and we'll look around.

13:06.995 --> 13:08.621
- We'll see what's there.
- Please just leave us alone!

13:08.622 --> 13:10.331
- [knocking]
- [Rudy] We're gonna go get a crowbar!

13:10.332 --> 13:12.500
[Vince] We're going to my apartment!
We're gonna get a crowbar!

13:12.501 --> 13:15.838
We're coming in no matter what, okay?
We're coming in!

13:16.547 --> 13:18.297
- Drop the gun!
- What?

13:18.298 --> 13:20.132
- [cocks gun]
- W-Wh-What is that?

13:20.133 --> 13:22.760
It's Eva Longoria's 19-in-one Multitool.

13:22.761 --> 13:24.679
At least four of the settings
could kill you!

13:24.680 --> 13:26.097
- [nails shoot]
- [Mabel and Oliver scream]

13:26.098 --> 13:28.140
- [Marshall grunts]
- [Oliver gasps]

13:28.141 --> 13:29.476
Okay, sit down!

13:29.977 --> 13:33.063
- [Marshall gasps]
- You fake-bearded bastard! Sit down!

13:35.440 --> 13:38.609
I need to know why. Why kill Sazz?

13:38.610 --> 13:41.654
Because she blackballed you as a stuntman?

13:41.655 --> 13:44.283
Sazz wrote the <i>Only Murders</i> movie.

13:45.742 --> 13:48.286
- Sazz, a writer?
- You stole the script from her?

13:48.287 --> 13:51.497
Look, I tried to become a writer.
I did what you're supposed to do.

13:51.498 --> 13:53.457
Took my childhood trauma
and tried to monetize it

13:53.458 --> 13:55.084
by turning it into a screenplay.

13:55.085 --> 13:56.544
And I had good trauma.

13:56.545 --> 13:57.962
Picture this.

13:57.963 --> 14:01.465
A dad who's a hunter
forces his son to be a hunter, too.

14:01.466 --> 14:03.509
And the kid is a perfect marksman.

14:03.510 --> 14:06.179
But all he wants to do is write.

14:06.180 --> 14:08.055
And when he leaves for Hollywood,

14:08.056 --> 14:10.642
the dad gives him six months. Says...

14:11.393 --> 14:14.103
[in gruff voice]
"You're a killer, not a writer."

14:14.104 --> 14:16.814
[normal] I mean, come on,
y-you'd watch that, right?

14:16.815 --> 14:19.567
- Well, depends on the casting.
- Would I have to go to the theater?

14:19.568 --> 14:20.735
I still haven't found time

14:20.736 --> 14:22.195
- to watch <i>The Wire.</i>
- No.

14:22.196 --> 14:25.531
I wanted to prove him wrong,
but nobody would touch my script!

14:25.532 --> 14:27.742
Which is not my fault!
Hollywood is broken!

14:27.743 --> 14:29.660
See, now here, I see his point.

14:29.661 --> 14:31.204
Why else would I not have an EGOT?

14:31.205 --> 14:32.289
- [chair drags]
- Freeze!

14:33.582 --> 14:36.626
I-I was about to call it quits
when I met Sazz.

14:36.627 --> 14:39.003
She was the first person to be kind to me.

14:39.004 --> 14:41.632
Sazz was kind to everyone.

14:42.674 --> 14:45.134
After the Ron Howard incident--

14:45.135 --> 14:46.803
and by the way, he overreacted--

14:47.554 --> 14:50.557
uh, Sazz said
my stunting career was over, but...

14:51.475 --> 14:53.559
now I could get back to my writing.

14:53.560 --> 14:56.896
Sh-She even offered to read
the latest draft of my screenplay.

14:56.897 --> 14:58.898
[Sazz]
Sure!

14:58.899 --> 15:00.483
I think I nailed it this time.

15:00.484 --> 15:03.653
- Oh, Rex. Man!
- [chuckles]

15:03.654 --> 15:07.699
You inspire me,
the way your words make me feel things.

15:10.077 --> 15:12.329
So much so that I gave it a whirl.

15:13.997 --> 15:15.665
You wrote something?

15:15.666 --> 15:17.792
You're the only one who knows.

15:17.793 --> 15:20.586
And my only copy. [sighs]

15:20.587 --> 15:24.549
And in the spirit of two writers
being vulnerable...

15:24.550 --> 15:25.800
[Marshall sighs]

15:25.801 --> 15:27.094
...would you give it a read?

15:28.804 --> 15:29.804
[Sazz laughs]

15:29.805 --> 15:33.392
I didn't have high hopes.
What did Sazz know about being a writer?

15:34.142 --> 15:35.394
But then, I started into it.

15:36.061 --> 15:37.979
<i>And it was good</i>.

15:37.980 --> 15:39.689
<i>Really fucking good.</i>

15:39.690 --> 15:41.859
<i>Certainly better than
anything I'd ever written.</i>

15:43.569 --> 15:45.904
Oh, you're done. [nervous laugh]

15:46.405 --> 15:48.115
[sighs]

15:49.992 --> 15:50.993
So?

15:51.618 --> 15:54.412
[Marshall] <i>That was the moment
where I could have been a friend,</i>

15:54.413 --> 15:56.956
<i>or I could have gone
in a completely different direction.</i>

15:56.957 --> 15:58.083
It's...

15:59.418 --> 16:00.752
not very good.

16:01.670 --> 16:04.381
But everybody's gotta start somewhere,
you know?

16:05.507 --> 16:08.259
How could Sazz write something
so great on her first try?

16:08.260 --> 16:09.552
<i>I-It wasn't fair</i>!

16:09.553 --> 16:13.181
I could make a copy and have a closer read
and see if I can come up with some fixes.

16:13.182 --> 16:15.684
Yes, please. That would be great.

16:16.643 --> 16:18.145
I-It's just the...

16:19.605 --> 16:22.064
It's all of it.
How much of this are you married to?

16:22.065 --> 16:24.859
So, I came up with a new name,
which was actually the hardest part.

16:24.860 --> 16:28.613
Eventually, I landed on Marshall P. Pope,
wh-which is awesome.

16:28.614 --> 16:30.656
- Is it, though?
- Sounds like a judge.

16:30.657 --> 16:33.743
After that, all I had to do was get
the script into the right hands.

16:33.744 --> 16:35.995
<i>I sent it all around town.
I knew someone would bite,</i>

16:35.996 --> 16:37.496
<i>but I was just trying to get an agent.</i>

16:37.497 --> 16:41.042
<i>Never in a million years did
I think it would get greenlit</i>.

16:41.043 --> 16:42.585
<i>A-And then fast-tracked?</i>

16:42.586 --> 16:44.879
<i>But Sazz found out.
She got shown the script</i>

16:44.880 --> 16:47.507
<i>by some stunt friends who were
looking for work on the movie.</i>

16:47.508 --> 16:50.343
I should have known something was up
when she invited me over for a drink.

16:50.344 --> 16:51.428
[knocking on door]

16:52.429 --> 16:53.471
Come in.

16:53.472 --> 16:55.974
[♪ tense, solemn music playing]

16:58.060 --> 16:59.061
[door shuts]

17:02.481 --> 17:03.940
Nice beard, Rex.

17:03.941 --> 17:05.484
Thanks.

17:05.943 --> 17:07.236
Have a seat.

17:12.407 --> 17:14.493
- [Marshall clears throat]
- [distant dog barking]

17:16.787 --> 17:17.787
[Sazz sighs]

17:17.788 --> 17:20.040
Or should I call you Marshall?

17:20.958 --> 17:22.750
The list of suspects wasn't long,

17:22.751 --> 17:25.711
but you were the only person
I let see the script.

17:25.712 --> 17:28.172
Sazz, this just got outta hand so quickly.

17:28.173 --> 17:29.507
I wanted to tell you, but--

17:29.508 --> 17:31.717
No, you didn't!
You told me the script was bad,

17:31.718 --> 17:33.052
and then you stole it from me!

17:33.053 --> 17:34.720
You know me, I can take a hit.

17:34.721 --> 17:37.765
Nearly lost a leg during <i>Police Academy 7.</i>

17:37.766 --> 17:38.850
But this?

17:38.851 --> 17:40.268
[♪ somber music playing]

17:40.269 --> 17:42.396
This hurts way more.

17:43.438 --> 17:45.898
Okay. I-I'm gonna call Bev Melon,
and we can--

17:45.899 --> 17:48.901
Bev what?
Are you making up new fake names now?!

17:48.902 --> 17:52.530
That's her real name!
Bev Melon f-from Paramount.

17:52.531 --> 17:54.323
She bought our script!

17:54.324 --> 17:58.327
This is not ours!

17:58.328 --> 18:00.998
[Sazz groans, sighs]

18:02.082 --> 18:03.417
This is mine!

18:03.542 --> 18:05.418
I hadn't even told Charles yet!

18:05.419 --> 18:08.505
I wanted to ask his permission
before I tried to sell it!

18:09.464 --> 18:12.049
Do you see the mess you've made here?

18:12.050 --> 18:14.093
I-I do, but...

18:14.094 --> 18:17.180
this movie is, is my dream.

18:17.181 --> 18:19.056
I had a dream, too!

18:19.057 --> 18:20.766
I had the dream to sell my script

18:20.767 --> 18:23.394
and-and-and build a trampoline park
in New Jersey!

18:23.395 --> 18:26.063
- A what?
- Never the fuck you mind.

18:26.064 --> 18:29.192
Sazz, if you say something about this,
I'll never live it down with my dad.

18:29.193 --> 18:30.777
W-With anyone!

18:31.528 --> 18:34.030
I don't know what I'll do

18:34.031 --> 18:35.948
if this gets out.

18:35.949 --> 18:37.951
♪

18:38.911 --> 18:40.828
Rex,

18:40.829 --> 18:42.915
I don't trust you anymore.

18:43.707 --> 18:45.875
Tomorrow, I'm gonna fly to New York

18:45.876 --> 18:49.253
to see Charles make his Broadway debut.

18:49.254 --> 18:51.005
And after, I'm gonna see him.

18:51.006 --> 18:52.591
And I'm sorry,

18:54.092 --> 18:55.760
but I gotta tell him.

18:55.761 --> 18:57.554
Can you please not do that?

18:58.430 --> 19:00.849
Out! Go!

19:01.517 --> 19:04.520
- [♪ somber music continues]
- [banging script]

19:10.526 --> 19:12.402
I'm really sorry, Sazz.

19:13.445 --> 19:14.947
[Sazz]
Yeah, me, too.

19:17.241 --> 19:18.699
[Marshall]
<i>What was I supposed to do?</i>

19:18.700 --> 19:21.078
Let her ruin everything I'd worked for?

19:22.704 --> 19:24.623
And then, I remembered
the Dudenoff apartment,

19:26.166 --> 19:27.668
<i>and I booked a red-eye.</i>

19:28.293 --> 19:30.711
[♪ ominous music playing]

19:30.712 --> 19:31.797
[window blinds rattle]

19:32.214 --> 19:35.842
<i>Sazz had included this whole
subplot in her first draft.</i>

19:35.843 --> 19:38.386
<i>Extraneous, if you ask me,
it's the first thing I cut,</i>

19:38.387 --> 19:40.847
<i>but I knew there was an empty apartment</i>

19:40.848 --> 19:42.181
<i>and what the code was to get in.</i>

19:42.182 --> 19:43.975
[gun snapping together]

19:43.976 --> 19:45.269
[cocks gun]

19:46.645 --> 19:49.273
[♪ ominous music continues]

19:49.940 --> 19:51.275
[gun sounds echoing]

19:55.821 --> 19:58.030
[♪ music swells]

19:58.031 --> 20:01.367
[panting]

20:01.368 --> 20:02.827
[whimpering]

20:02.828 --> 20:04.620
<i>I couldn't do it.</i>

20:04.621 --> 20:07.123
It's okay. It's okay.
You're not a killer. [panting]

20:07.124 --> 20:09.125
You're not a killer.
You're a writer. [gasps]

20:09.126 --> 20:10.835
You're not a killer. You're a writer.

20:10.836 --> 20:12.962
You're not a killer.
You're a writer. [sobs]

20:12.963 --> 20:15.339
You're a writer. You're a writer.

20:15.340 --> 20:18.050
[gasps] You're a writer. You're a writer.

20:18.051 --> 20:21.638
[♪ percussive piano notes play]

20:22.848 --> 20:24.849
No, I'm fucking not. [gasps]

20:24.850 --> 20:26.601
[♪ dramatic music playing]

20:26.602 --> 20:27.852
<i>But...</i>

20:27.853 --> 20:29.353
<i>maybe...</i>

20:29.354 --> 20:31.731
<i>maybe to be a writer,</i>

20:31.732 --> 20:33.358
<i>I had to become a killer.</i>

20:35.194 --> 20:37.320
[gunshot, glass shatters]

20:37.321 --> 20:39.739
[unloads, casing clatters]

20:39.740 --> 20:42.283
[clattering echoes]

20:42.284 --> 20:44.411
[♪ somber music playing]

20:44.578 --> 20:45.786
[footsteps stomp]

20:45.787 --> 20:47.122
[breathing heavily]

20:47.706 --> 20:50.083
<i>Only she didn't die.</i>

20:50.667 --> 20:52.294
<i>I had to think quick.</i>

20:53.086 --> 20:55.088
<i>One reason I made a good stuntman</i>?

20:55.839 --> 20:58.382
<i>No fear of heights.</i>

20:58.383 --> 20:59.718
[zips bag]

21:03.847 --> 21:04.848
[blinds rattle]

21:05.390 --> 21:06.390
[window shuts]

21:06.391 --> 21:08.560
[wind blowing]

21:08.769 --> 21:11.688
♪

21:15.192 --> 21:18.277
[Sazz choking]

21:18.278 --> 21:21.865
- [wind whistling]
- [Sazz gasping]

21:26.119 --> 21:28.955
[wind whistling]

21:28.956 --> 21:30.415
[window opens]

21:34.920 --> 21:37.338
[labored breathing]

21:37.339 --> 21:40.425
I'm sorry it had to end this way.
I just...

21:41.927 --> 21:43.178
I need this.

21:43.470 --> 21:45.346
[Sazz straining, raggedly breathing]

21:45.347 --> 21:48.141
Where's the script?
The one with your name on it?

21:48.684 --> 21:51.061
[straining] He's gonna get you.

21:51.562 --> 21:53.814
Who? Who will?

21:54.439 --> 21:55.899
My...

21:57.192 --> 21:58.652
number...

22:01.321 --> 22:02.865
one.

22:04.408 --> 22:06.535
♪

22:09.079 --> 22:10.580
[Charles]
<i>So, you watched her die,</i>

22:10.581 --> 22:13.417
and you threw her down the trash chute
like she was garbage.

22:14.001 --> 22:15.501
Think of it as her final stunt.

22:15.502 --> 22:17.211
- [gasps]
- [multitool buzzes]

22:17.212 --> 22:18.754
It's on the vibrator setting!

22:18.755 --> 22:20.131
[Oliver]
Dammit, Eva Longoria!

22:20.132 --> 22:21.799
- [Mabel Mora] Charles, fix it!
- [Oliver growls]

22:21.800 --> 22:23.802
- [Marshall gasps]
- [♪ dramatic music playing]

22:24.136 --> 22:25.511
- [Marshall grunts]
- [Oliver yelps]

22:25.512 --> 22:26.597
[Mabel]
Oliver!

22:27.139 --> 22:28.681
[Marshall yells, grunts]

22:28.682 --> 22:30.099
[panting]

22:30.100 --> 22:33.811
Okay, next time, let's not have our killer
be a professional stuntman.

22:33.812 --> 22:35.730
There is no next time!

22:35.731 --> 22:37.106
Maybe my dad was right.

22:37.107 --> 22:39.233
This is my talent.

22:39.234 --> 22:41.068
- [Oliver and Mabel whimper]
- [Marshall] So,

22:41.069 --> 22:43.279
welcome to the end of your movie.

22:43.280 --> 22:44.906
- [all three whimpering]
- [♪ music swells]

22:44.907 --> 22:45.990
- [gunshot]
- [Marshall gasps]

22:45.991 --> 22:47.201
[Oliver and Mabel shriek]

22:47.951 --> 22:49.953
- [body thuds]
- [gun clatters]

22:50.662 --> 22:52.079
[blood seeping]

22:52.080 --> 22:54.625
♪

22:55.042 --> 22:57.211
- God.
- What? What?

22:58.545 --> 22:59.546
[Mabel gasps]

23:04.426 --> 23:05.844
No fucking way.

23:09.473 --> 23:11.058
♪

23:14.730 --> 23:17.397
[police chatter]

23:24.530 --> 23:26.030
How did you get into my apartment?

23:26.031 --> 23:27.366
I never left.

23:28.784 --> 23:30.910
You've been hiding in my closet
for three weeks?

23:30.911 --> 23:32.662
And the secret passageways.

23:32.663 --> 23:34.497
I was just waiting for you
to figure out the case,

23:34.498 --> 23:36.791
so I could exact my revenge.

23:36.792 --> 23:39.418
We did it together, Charles. For Sazz.

23:39.419 --> 23:43.090
I'm good at seeing through
tiny slits and window blinds,

23:43.465 --> 23:47.218
but I would much rather have taken
Marshall out up close, you know?

23:47.219 --> 23:50.555
Stabbed him through the eye
with a buck knife

23:50.556 --> 23:52.766
and really mixed it around.

23:54.017 --> 23:57.187
I truly don't know how you
make words like that arousing.

23:57.604 --> 23:59.063
Oh, Charles.

23:59.064 --> 24:00.189
Oh, by the way,

24:00.190 --> 24:03.401
I ate a bunch of your Pirate Booty
when I was in hiding.

24:03.402 --> 24:05.319
I'll Venmo you eight bucks.

24:05.320 --> 24:08.072
Call it even for serial killing
our serial killer.

24:08.073 --> 24:09.283
[officer]
I've got her, let's go.

24:10.409 --> 24:12.577
- Goodbye, Jan.
- It's not goodbye, Charles.

24:12.578 --> 24:15.163
It never is with us. We're endgame.

24:18.667 --> 24:19.877
[Oliver]
Bye.

24:20.377 --> 24:22.253
Well, it's hard to deny
you make a cute couple.

24:22.254 --> 24:23.337
Oh God!

24:23.338 --> 24:26.216
Seems like an awkward time to celebrate.

24:27.676 --> 24:30.303
- Although, I have an out-of-the-box idea.
- [♪ curious music playing]

24:30.304 --> 24:32.805
Isn't it insulting to flirt now?

24:32.806 --> 24:35.558
Oh, who the hell knows?
Suddenly, it's rude to tell a secretary

24:35.559 --> 24:37.560
- she looks pretty in a pair of slacks.
- [Eugene Levy] Hm.

24:37.561 --> 24:40.646
Nope. No to that whole sentence.

24:40.647 --> 24:42.440
Compliment her purse.

24:42.441 --> 24:45.318
If it isn't on their body,
you can like it. [snorts]

24:45.319 --> 24:49.030
[Eva Longoria] No, again, to every word
that's coming out of your mouth.

24:49.031 --> 24:51.073
[sighs] I'm glad you're doing this.

24:51.074 --> 24:54.410
- Being alone in life is making you weird.
- [Eugene] Thank you?

24:54.411 --> 24:56.662
- [Trina Brothers] And cut!
- Okay, okay.

24:56.663 --> 24:59.207
- [sighs] Are you gonna snort like that?
- Well, he does.

24:59.208 --> 25:00.833
- Yeah.
- [Trina speaks indistinctly]

25:00.834 --> 25:05.087
Poor bastards, think they just have
to solve Tim Kono's murder.

25:05.088 --> 25:08.341
Little do they know the bodies
just keep on droppin'.

25:08.342 --> 25:11.135
Oh, there you go again,
saying Loretta's gonna get murdered.

25:11.136 --> 25:13.554
- I didn't say--
- E-Every time I have a big moment,

25:13.555 --> 25:16.390
an opening night,
someone dies just to spite me.

25:16.391 --> 25:18.893
- Loretta is fine.
- Hey, guys!

25:18.894 --> 25:20.561
Are we amazing or what? [laughs]

25:20.562 --> 25:22.688
- [Charles] It's good!
- [Mabel] Doing a good job.

25:22.689 --> 25:25.191
My level of cringe is mercifully low.

25:25.192 --> 25:26.567
[soft laugh]

25:26.568 --> 25:28.361
Heard you caught the killer.

25:28.362 --> 25:30.321
Couldn't have done it without us.

25:30.322 --> 25:33.115
Although I'm not entirely
sure what we did,

25:33.116 --> 25:34.825
but, uh, can't say it didn't help.

25:34.826 --> 25:37.245
I knew that guy Marshall
was a shitty writer.

25:37.246 --> 25:40.623
He was trying to get my character to say
"not" after each sentence.

25:40.624 --> 25:42.583
I loved it. Not.

25:42.584 --> 25:44.919
[laughter]

25:44.920 --> 25:47.505
Mabel! I have great news.

25:47.506 --> 25:50.049
So, I set our pitch meeting for next week.

25:50.050 --> 25:52.260
So, I hope you've been
fleshing out your ideas

25:52.261 --> 25:53.970
- about the buttons.
- [Mabel] You know what?

25:53.971 --> 25:56.597
I'd rather tell the story of a stuntwoman

25:56.598 --> 26:00.601
who dedicated her whole life
to protecting her friend.

26:00.602 --> 26:03.271
Who wrote a love letter to him

26:03.272 --> 26:05.022
in the form of a movie.

26:05.023 --> 26:07.733
- [♪ soft music playing]
- [Bev Melon] Right, but the thing is,

26:07.734 --> 26:10.361
our algorithm really likes buttons.

26:10.362 --> 26:12.613
I don't think I belong in this industry.

26:12.614 --> 26:15.491
- [musical ringtone]
- Wait one second. Hello?

26:15.492 --> 26:16.826
[mouthing] One second.

26:16.827 --> 26:17.952
Yeah.

26:17.953 --> 26:20.121
[Tawny Brothers]
We need to keep shooting, people.

26:20.122 --> 26:21.247
[Eugene]
Excuse me.

26:21.248 --> 26:23.250
[set production chatter]

26:24.084 --> 26:28.087
You know, I appreciate this movie
in a whole different way now.

26:28.088 --> 26:31.299
- I mean, Sazz wrote this.
- Aww, Charles.

26:31.300 --> 26:33.594
[♪ soft music continues]

26:41.602 --> 26:43.186
Hey.

26:43.187 --> 26:44.854
Sorry you're missing all this.

26:44.855 --> 26:46.647
Yeah.

26:46.648 --> 26:48.150
Would've been nice.

26:50.068 --> 26:51.612
I think this is your chair.

26:52.154 --> 26:55.282
[sighs] Well, thank you, my friend.

26:55.574 --> 26:57.658
[inhales, exhales]

26:57.659 --> 26:58.785
[clears throat]

27:01.872 --> 27:03.415
Actually, I miss that guy.

27:05.834 --> 27:07.002
You did good.

27:08.086 --> 27:11.173
I know this is just me
telling myself I did good, but...

27:12.174 --> 27:13.634
I'll take the compliment.

27:15.636 --> 27:19.181
♪

27:21.767 --> 27:23.268
It's been a long day.

27:24.144 --> 27:25.686
Let him talk to himself.

27:25.687 --> 27:27.606
[Charles laughs]

27:29.566 --> 27:31.359
[♪ "Chapel of Love"
by The Dixie Cups playing]

27:31.360 --> 27:33.319
<i>♪ Going to the chapel and we're ♪</i>

27:33.320 --> 27:36.698
<i>♪ Gonna get married ♪</i>

27:37.407 --> 27:41.035
<i>- ♪ Going to the chapel and we're ♪</i>
- [Winnie softly whining]

27:41.036 --> 27:44.914
<i>♪ Gonna get married ♪</i>

27:44.915 --> 27:47.291
<i>♪ Gee, I really love you ♪</i>

27:47.292 --> 27:52.588
<i>♪ And we're gonna get married ♪</i>

27:52.589 --> 27:57.177
<i>♪ Going to the chapel of love ♪</i>

27:59.096 --> 28:00.097
[Oliver giggles]

28:00.764 --> 28:02.515
<i>♪ Spring is here ♪</i>

28:02.516 --> 28:06.561
<i>♪ The sky is blue ♪</i>

28:06.562 --> 28:08.646
<i>♪ Whoa-ho-ho ♪</i>

28:08.647 --> 28:12.483
<i>♪ Birds all sing as if... ♪</i>

28:12.484 --> 28:14.068
Okay, where is she?

28:14.069 --> 28:15.903
- She's coming.
- Yeah, any second.

28:15.904 --> 28:17.905
No, no, s-something has happened.

28:17.906 --> 28:19.198
- Oliver.
- Oliver. Just...

28:19.199 --> 28:21.951
<i>♪ We'll say, I do and-- ♪</i>

28:21.952 --> 28:24.412
- [Uma screams]
- [♪ song stops abruptly]

28:24.413 --> 28:26.581
Sorry. I thought I saw a roach.

28:26.582 --> 28:28.416
[guests murmuring]

28:28.417 --> 28:31.628
[distant church bell tolling]

28:35.716 --> 28:38.719
[♪ gentle music playing]

28:40.012 --> 28:42.014
[birds chirping]

28:44.474 --> 28:46.435
♪

28:50.939 --> 28:51.940
[Mabel softly chuckles]

28:52.274 --> 28:53.775
[Will sighs]

28:54.484 --> 28:56.194
[softly] Sorry, we lost track of time.

28:56.195 --> 28:58.237
- We had a lot of catching up to do.
- [laughing] Yeah.

28:58.238 --> 28:59.948
[♪ gentle music continues]

29:02.075 --> 29:03.368
[softly] Love you.

29:09.124 --> 29:10.124
[soft laughter]

29:10.125 --> 29:12.001
♪

29:12.002 --> 29:14.670
[muffled vowing]

29:14.671 --> 29:16.340
♪

29:19.343 --> 29:21.761
For the rest of your life, I promise...

29:21.762 --> 29:25.723
Be my man, be my husband,
be my friend, be my lover.

29:25.724 --> 29:27.976
- [excited laughter]
- [applause]

29:31.355 --> 29:33.356
[soft laughing]

29:33.357 --> 29:36.944
- [♪ merengue music playing]
- [excited chatter, laughter]

29:41.156 --> 29:42.699
♪

29:49.665 --> 29:50.958
- [glasses clink]
- [Charles chuckles]

29:51.416 --> 29:53.543
- [♪ merengue music fades out]
- [Oliver] Well, well, well, well,

29:53.544 --> 29:56.671
- we put on a good show, Mrs. Putnam.
- [Loretta Durkin] Aww.

29:56.672 --> 29:59.090
Yeah. Mrs. Durkin-Putnam.

29:59.091 --> 30:01.176
- Ah.
- You forgot my hyphen.

30:02.386 --> 30:04.136
- Forgot it?
- Mm-hmm.

30:04.137 --> 30:05.763
It's all I think about.

30:05.764 --> 30:09.560
[both laugh]

30:10.936 --> 30:14.480
You are the most extraordinary man
I have ever known.

30:14.481 --> 30:16.607
- Ah... thank you.
- You are.

30:16.608 --> 30:18.526
You brought down a murderer,

30:18.527 --> 30:20.570
and you can merengue.

30:20.571 --> 30:23.531
- I mean...
- Mm. What a combo.

30:23.532 --> 30:25.533
[♪ "When I Fall in Love With You"
by Nat King Cole playing]

30:25.534 --> 30:26.701
- Here it is!
- [laughs] No!

30:26.702 --> 30:27.785
[Loretta]
I can't.

30:27.786 --> 30:29.537
I just...

30:29.538 --> 30:31.330
I can't imagine,

30:31.331 --> 30:33.082
taking you away from all this.

30:33.083 --> 30:35.209
What are you talking about? I-I...

30:35.210 --> 30:37.211
I can't wait to be in New Zealand.

30:37.212 --> 30:39.130
You know, with all the...

30:39.131 --> 30:41.341
[sniffs, sighs] sheep.

30:42.050 --> 30:44.135
Anyway...

30:44.136 --> 30:45.511
I'll be with you.

30:45.512 --> 30:47.305
Mm-hmm.

30:47.306 --> 30:49.390
But, you won't be with them.

30:49.391 --> 30:52.810
<i>- ♪ It will be completely ♪</i>
- Mwah!

30:52.811 --> 30:55.521
- [giggles] Okay.
- [Charles laughs]

30:55.522 --> 30:56.982
[gasps] Aw.

30:57.191 --> 31:00.318
<i>♪ Or I'll never give my heart ♪</i>

31:00.319 --> 31:02.362
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

31:02.905 --> 31:06.157
Ollie, we got our happy ending, didn't we?

31:06.158 --> 31:08.284
- Yeah, we did.
- And nothing in our relationship

31:08.285 --> 31:11.370
has ever been even vaguely conventional.

31:11.371 --> 31:14.123
So, why should we start now?

31:14.124 --> 31:17.710
<i>♪ You feel that way too... ♪</i>

31:17.711 --> 31:19.504
[Oliver]
Let's talk about it tonight.

31:19.505 --> 31:21.590
[both laugh]

31:23.258 --> 31:24.301
[♪ song fades out]

31:25.135 --> 31:27.386
Did Oliver and Loretta go up already?

31:27.387 --> 31:29.388
Yeah. She leaves first thing,

31:29.389 --> 31:31.474
so I think they're...

31:31.475 --> 31:33.476
taking care of their honeymoon business

31:33.477 --> 31:34.852
while they can.

31:34.853 --> 31:38.439
Let's just pretend they're upstairs
playing show tunes on the piano.

31:38.440 --> 31:41.527
Well, my date and I had a grand old time.

31:42.861 --> 31:44.320
You brought the ashes?

31:44.321 --> 31:45.821
Yeah, Sazz loved weddings,

31:45.822 --> 31:48.366
but I'm gonna say goodbye to these.

31:48.367 --> 31:51.786
Sprinkle 'em on the land that Sazz wanted
for her trampoline park.

31:51.787 --> 31:53.621
I think that's where she'd like to end up.

31:53.622 --> 31:54.706
[elevator dings]

31:55.707 --> 31:58.168
Mr. Savage? Ms. Mora.

31:59.461 --> 32:02.213
I-I hope it's okay.
I was upstairs looking for you.

32:02.214 --> 32:04.924
There was no doorman on duty.
I took a shot.

32:04.925 --> 32:07.468
- I'm sorry, do we know you?
- No.

32:07.469 --> 32:09.846
I'll send it back down for you.

32:09.847 --> 32:11.306
If I feel like it.

32:11.431 --> 32:13.934
- [Charles sighs]
- [elevator closes]

32:14.518 --> 32:17.603
I wanna hire you to find my husband.
It's urgent.

32:17.604 --> 32:20.064
Oh, w-we're not a detective firm.

32:20.065 --> 32:22.984
- [♪ curious music playing]
- My husband is Nicky Caccimelio.

32:22.985 --> 32:25.863
O-Or was, if you believe the news.

32:26.697 --> 32:28.614
I pay very well.

32:28.615 --> 32:31.284
We only investigate
murders in the building.

32:31.285 --> 32:33.369
It's right there in our name.

32:33.370 --> 32:36.999
What happened to Nicky has everything
to do with this building.

32:38.000 --> 32:39.918
I'm sorry, but good luck.

32:40.586 --> 32:42.211
I'm disappointed.

32:42.212 --> 32:44.255
I-I thought maybe you could do

32:44.256 --> 32:46.090
what the police have been unable to

32:46.091 --> 32:49.302
and what I can't safely do by myself.

32:49.303 --> 32:52.097
Sofia Caccimelio.

32:52.598 --> 32:55.100
- [elevator dings]
- Call if you change your mind.

33:04.234 --> 33:05.736
That's quite a dame.

33:06.862 --> 33:08.779
In the same way that Judi Dench is a dame.

33:08.780 --> 33:10.365
Good save.

33:12.326 --> 33:14.202
[ambient street noise]

33:14.203 --> 33:16.913
[Loretta] You are gonna come,
though, in a, in a few weeks?

33:16.914 --> 33:18.789
[in Kiwi accent]
You're not gonna leave me high and dry

33:18.790 --> 33:20.875
in New Zealand, are ya?

33:20.876 --> 33:22.168
[Oliver]
You can't Kiwi me away.

33:22.169 --> 33:24.045
- [both laugh]
- [♪ gentle music playing]

33:24.046 --> 33:26.047
♪

33:26.048 --> 33:27.132
[Oliver] Sorry.

33:36.016 --> 33:38.143
Where have you been?

33:42.731 --> 33:43.732
[sighs]

33:48.320 --> 33:49.446
[snorts]

33:50.113 --> 33:51.114
[chuckles]

33:51.782 --> 33:53.867
[Loretta laughs]

33:56.370 --> 33:57.371
[sighs]

34:01.416 --> 34:02.918
- [car engine starts]
- I love you.

34:09.967 --> 34:13.470
And as the last frames flicker
on our season at the movies,

34:14.221 --> 34:17.015
between newlyweds and a captured killer,

34:18.016 --> 34:21.979
we somehow managed to find
our way to a happy ending.

34:22.396 --> 34:26.357
And got through a whole wedding day
all without a body.

34:26.358 --> 34:27.692
[♪ gentle music playing]

34:27.693 --> 34:29.778
- [phone beeps]
- We must be doing something right.

34:30.487 --> 34:31.488
[Mabel chuckles]

34:33.615 --> 34:35.617
- [Oliver] Mm.
- Beautiful day.

34:37.035 --> 34:38.327
Feel that breeze, huh?

34:38.328 --> 34:40.831
- It's nice to take a moment and enjoy.
- Yeah.

34:41.498 --> 34:42.623
Wait.

34:42.624 --> 34:44.250
Oh, my God!

34:44.251 --> 34:46.002
- [♪ dramatic music playing]
- [Oliver gasps]

34:46.003 --> 34:47.129
Lester?

34:47.880 --> 34:50.381
- Lester!
- Call 911!

34:50.382 --> 34:54.135
- [♪ eerie vocalizing]
- Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

34:54.136 --> 34:55.720
Lester!

34:55.721 --> 34:56.929
[line ringing]

34:56.930 --> 34:59.473
- [Oliver whimpers]
- [Mabel] No! No, no, no, no!

34:59.474 --> 35:02.852
- [Charles] Oh, my God, no! Lester!
- [Mabel whimpers]

35:02.853 --> 35:04.187
[line continues ringing]

35:04.188 --> 35:06.564
[operator] [on phone]
<i>Thank you for calling 911.</i>

35:06.565 --> 35:10.151
<i>There are... 72 emergencies ahead of you.</i>

35:10.152 --> 35:13.238
[♪ vocalizing building]

35:21.413 --> 35:24.416
[♪ "Hooray For Hollywood"
by Anita O'Day playing]

35:27.044 --> 35:30.087
<i>♪ Hooray for Hollywood ♪</i>

35:30.088 --> 35:33.341
<i>♪ That screwy booey hooey Hollywood ♪</i>

35:33.342 --> 35:36.552
<i>♪ Where any office boy or young mechanic ♪</i>

35:36.553 --> 35:38.346
<i>♪ Can be a panic ♪</i>

